&gt;Hi Richard,
&gt;
&gt;Looks like a kozuka-ana to me. The shape of the ana would be more indicative
&gt;of a kogai rather than the size. Some early stuff with what can be taken as
&gt;ubu-ana can be either very large or very small. Ko-Mino kogai come in a wild
&gt;variety of sizes including pencil thin ones.
&gt;
&gt;Gordon
&gt;  -----Original Message-----
&gt;  From: Richard George [mailto:rkg@...]
&gt;  Sent: Friday, April 25, 2003 2:18 PM
&gt;  To: nihontostudy@yahoogroups.com
&gt;  Subject: Re: [nihontostudy] Re: katana vs wakizashi
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;  Hi,
&gt;
&gt;  Could it be that a some of these &quot;uchigatana sized&quot; tsuba got flipped
&gt;  over and the kogai ana used for kozuka ana?
&gt;
&gt;  I have one piece where the side where most of the banging is around the
&gt;  nakago ana would iply the hitsu ana was for a kozuka, but
&gt;  from the shape the ana itself kind of looks  like it might have been for
&gt;  a kogai, and there is some banging on the other side
&gt;  that looks like they originally did on these pieces - check out:
&gt;
&gt;  http://home.teleport.com/~rkg/photos/tsuba/tosho3_front_small.JPG
&gt;  http://home.teleport.com/~rkg/photos/tsuba/tosho3_back_small.JPG
&gt;
&gt;  Another couple of  explanations I&#39;d posit is that perhaps there were a
&gt;  LOT more uchigatana
&gt;  that weren&#39;t katana length or that perhaps  people were turning their
&gt;  uchigatana into
&gt;  wakizashi via shortening when it became the rage to have a
&gt;  wakizashi.  It seems that a lot of the early tachi fittings got reused
&gt;  in various ways - could it be that
&gt;  a lot of these pieces got &quot;recycled&quot; into wakizashi one way or another,
&gt;  hence the large number of early tsuba that have
&gt;  the kozuka ana?.
&gt;
&gt;  donning the asbestos underwear...
&gt;
&gt;  rkg
&gt;  (Richard George)
&gt;
&gt;  &gt;Hi,
&gt;  &gt;Just time for a partial answer.  From early koshirae I have seen, katana
&gt;are mounted with kogai only, kozuka and kogai, or neither.  I have not seen
&gt;a katana mounted with only a kozuka.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;Wakizashi are very commonly mounted with only a kozuka, but are also seen
&gt;with kozuka and kogai.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;The two files in the nihontostudy website File section include columns to
&gt;indicate the kozuka and kogai configuration for each mounting in the Katana
&gt;Koshirae catalog.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;We see a fair number of 8+ cm tsuba around with a kozuka ana cut in
&gt;them...  were they really big wakizashi tsuba, were katana mounted with
&gt;kozuka only at some point or was the ana used for a kogai, despite the
&gt;kozuka shape?  I don&#39;t know.  There is one wakizashi koshirae in the spread
&gt;sheet with an 8.6 cm tsuba, so that might be the explanation.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;I&#39;ll come back to this later.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;Jim
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;  Ken -
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;  Presence of kogai and kozuka ana are maybe part of the
&gt;  &gt;  story. I asked Jim a similar question and as I understood
&gt;  &gt;  his reply (perhaps he will elaborate); katana tsuba
&gt;  &gt;  normally have both kozuka and kogai ana or either
&gt;  &gt;  while wakizashi tsuba normally only have a kozuka ana.
&gt;  &gt;  Although there are numerous exceptions; small sukashi
&gt;  &gt;  tsuba which to my eye are obviously for a wakizashi
&gt;  &gt;  based on size not uncommonly have both. Also many
&gt;  &gt;  of the very early tosho and katchushi tsuba had
&gt;  &gt;  only one (many had been added later). I hope I haven&#39;t
&gt;  &gt;  done too much damage to what Jim had said. I&#39;m sure
&gt;  &gt;  he will fill in the blanks.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;  Rich
